I looked into this and found that the underlying Grammar Tree algorithm introduces additional overhead due to frequent CPU–GPU synchronization during the decoding phase. On the RTX 4090, which has lower concurrency, this leads to higher scheduling costs. In contrast, the H100—with its higher concurrency and support for advanced features like parallel streams—is able to hide much of this overhead.

In real-world commercial applications, the RTX 4090 offers a very high cost-performance ratio when serving 8B-scale models. Therefore, we would like to kindly ask whether the vLLM team could look into optimizing xgrammar and vLLM v1 for better acceleration on the RTX 4090.

### Alternatives

So far, we’ve only made some partial optimizations on top of vLLM 0.6.4, specifically around Outlines and improvements to the guide_json input interface. However, these are not fundamental solutions. Our goal is to follow and adopt the latest versions of vLLM, and we would greatly prefer improvements that are compatible with vLLM v1 and xgrammar.

